Continual Defense Against Evolving Jailbreaks: A
Multi-Agent Adversarial Framework with Linear
Gating MoE
Qianqiao Xu
College of Computer Science and Technology National University of Defense Technology Changsha, China xuqianqiao23@nudt.edu.cn
Feng Liu*
College of Computer Science and Technology National University of Defense Technology Changsha, China *richardlf@nudt.edu.cn
Abstract—Large Language Models (LLMs) are vulnerable to deceptive jailbreak attacks inducing harmful outputs. Existing defenses suffer from catastrophic forgetting in continual defense learning against evolving attacks. To address the limited space issue caused by defenders attempting to reduce defense forgetting when learning long sequence tasks, we propose a Mixture-ofExperts (MoE) based continual defense learning method, which only activates the most suitable experts to learn new tasks and freezes the other experts to prevent forgetting the old defense tasks. Our approach employs in-context learning (ICL) to simulate an attack-defense LLM-based multi-agent framework, where an attacker generates sequential novel attacks, a defender continuously learns to counter the attacker, and an evaluator assesses the defense. Crucially, we introduce a linear gating MoE continual learning method for the defender. This method uses a linear gate to assign new attack tasks to specific expert networks (formed by partitioning model neurons), isolating training to prevent forgetting of established defenses. Experiments demonstrate that our framework significantly outperforms baselines in continual defense learning, achieving higher defense success rates across sequentially updated attack tasks.
Keywords—continual defense learning, Mixture-of-Experts, multi-agent, large language model
I. INTRODUCTION
With the impressive capabilities demonstrated by large language models (LLMs) in natural language generation tasks, concerns about their safety have become increasingly prominent, especially when facing deceptive jailbreak attacks[1]. Attackers often attempt to induce LLMs into generating harmful, biased, or even illegal content[2]. In response, researchers have proposed various defense strategies against the attackers.
Prompt engineering[3] prompts LLMs to generate safe responses against the attack without requiring model parameter updates. Wu et al.[4] prompt LLMs to verify that their generated content is safe to defend against attacks. Wei et al.[5] shows LLMs the safe demonstration of not producing harmful responses. However, these methods typically employ static inference procedures, which cannot accumulate reusable defense knowledge from prior interactions, thereby limiting their effectiveness against sophisticated and frequently evolving attacks[6]. In contrast, instruction finetuning typically enhances the model's robustness against evolving attacks[7]. Mart[8] finetunes LLMs with safe defense samples to strengthen
their defense capabilities. Wan et al.[9] fintune the model to detect the harmful inputs. However, these approaches cannot be adapted to continuous learning (CL) scenarios that require defending against continuously evolving attackers generating iteratively reinforced sequential attacks. Their poor CL capabilities may cause them to forget previously learned defense methods against consistently updated attack tasks[10].
There are two CL methods to mitigate defense forgetting: (1) Rehearsal-based CL methods mitigate forgetting by storing data from learned tasks for retraining. Yang et al.[11] continuously detoxify the old attack problem before finetuning the new defense task. Deng et al.[7] reduce forgetting by backtracking to train LLM on old defense tasks that are not defended successfully. (2) Architecture-based CL methods reduce forgetting by incorporating task-relevant training modules into the model structure. SafeMerge[12] reduces forgetting by training different defense models independently and then fusing them. Wistuba et al.[13] set up structures in the model to be responsible for different defense tasks to reduce the coverage of old tasks. However, these traditional approaches require additional structural space to store information about old defense tasks, which is resource-consuming for defending against long sequences of iteratively updated attacks.
In this paper, we propose a Mixture of Experts (MoE) based CL defense method, which only activates the most suitable defense experts against the new attacks to reduce the additional space required for mitigating the forgetting of old defense tasks. Specifically, we construct an LLM-based multi-agent attack and defense framework to generate iteratively updated sequential defense tasks. We use in-context learning (ICL) to enable LLMs to act as different agents, including an attacker (iteratively generating new attack tasks), a defender (continuously learning to defend against new attacks), and an evaluator (evaluating whether the defense is successful or not). We propose a linear gating MoE CL method for the defender to reduce the storage space for mitigating the forgetting of learning a long sequence of defense tasks. We first use a linear gate mechanism to assign specific experts to new attack tasks for defense training. Then, we design a defense expert network, which partitions the FNN layers of the model into nonoverlapping groups of neurons, each serving as an expert responsible for a different defense training task. This approach ensures that the acquired defense capabilities are not overwritten and forgotten by the learning of new tasks. We conduct experiments on our methods with LLMs and test the
