Our contributions are threefold: (1) We propose using MOE in CL defense tasks to reduce the storage space required to avoid forgetting in learning against long sequence attack tasks. (2) We construct a MOE-based multi-agent CL defense framework, which utilizes ICL to enable LLMs to play different roles in generating defense tasks continuously and assigns different defense tasks to MoE's experts to reduce the overlap in CL between learning new tasks and old tasks. (3) Experiments show that our method outperforms other baselines in continuous defense learning tasks.
II. METHOD
A. Overview
As shown in Figure 1, we propose a MoE-based multi-agent continual learning defense framework to mitigate defense forgetting when LLMs continually learn to defend against iteratively enhanced attacks. We first construct an LLM-based multi-agent continual attack and defense system (Sec. B), which comprises an attacker that continually generates attacks, a defender that responds to the attacks with a safe response, and an evaluator that assesses the defense's success and provides feedback to the other two agents to enhance their abilities. We then propose a linear gating MOE continual learning method for the defender (Sec. C) to mitigate the defender's forgetting when it continually learns to defend sequential attack tasks provided by the attacker.
Figure 1: MoE-based multi-agent continual learning defense framework.
B. LLM-based multi-agent attack-defense framework
We utilize ICL to instruct LLMs to engage in different agent roles, simulating a continuous attack-defense scenario and generating iteratively updated sequential defense tasks. This framework contains three agents: (1) Attacker. The attacker continually generates various attacks against the defender. We utilize in-context learning (ICL) to prompt the LLM to generate multiple types of attack prompts and refine those that are unsuccessful. (2) Defender. The defender defends against the attacker's attacks. We use the ICL to guide the LLM in generating a safe response against the attacker. (3) Evaluator. The evaluator assesses whether the defense is successful and provides feedback to both the attacker and the defender. Following Deng. et al.[7], we prompt the LLM to score the safety of the response generated by the defender on a scale of 1 to 10. We consider the defense successful if the score is 5 or less.
The interaction flows between three agents. The attacker first generates attack prompts to attack the defender. The defender then generates a safe response against the attacker. The evaluator scores the response and evaluates whether the defense is successful. If the defense succeeds, the evaluator gives the attack failure results back to the attacker, and the
attacker uses the ICL technique to strengthen the attack. If the defense fails, the evaluator feeds the results back to the defender, and the defender uses the defense failure samples to learn to strengthen the defense's ability.
C. Linear gating MOE continual learning defender
To reduce storage space for mitigating forgetting in constantly learning defenses against new tasks generated by the attacker, we propose a MoE-based defender that allocates only the relevant defense experts to learn the new task and freezes the others. Since the defender continuously learns long sequences of defense tasks that are updated iteratively, traditional continuous learning methods often lack sufficient space to store data from old tasks for retraining the entire model's parameters[14,15]. In contrast, MOE can assign and activate the parameter space of the most suitable experts to the new task while freezing other internal structures[16,17]. This strategy reduces the likelihood of forgetting previous tasks without necessitating additional storage space for retraining. Therefore, we proposed MOE for the defender to mitigate defense forgetting in learning the long sequence of tasks, where we use a linear gate (Sec.II.C.1) to select the most relevant experts for each task and allocate them to the defense experts
