III. EXPERIMENTS
A. Experiment settings
We first construct a CL defense benchmark to evaluate our method. It includes four defense tasks against different types of attacks: (1) Defending against human red-teaming attacks. We select HH-RedTeam[18], which has 9739 manually constructed attack prompts. (2) Defend LLM red-teaming attack. We choose SAP[7] which contains the LLMs' automatically generated harmful questions. (3) Defend templated-based attack. We utilize LatentJailbreak[18] as the defense dataset, which includes various jailbreak templates designed to induce LLMs to generate harmful content. (4) Defend the promptprompt attack. AutoDan[19] utilizes ICL to enable the LLMs to conceal the attacking intent of the attack prompt. Then, we use gpt4o to generate responses for these four datasets as labels for the defense datasets following Wang et al.[20]. We test our method on deepseek-16b using three different dataset orders and calculate the average defend success rate (Avg_DSR) over four defense datasets in each order to evaluate our method.
We compare our method with three baselines. (1) Instruct finetune (FT)[21]. A multi-task learning method separately trains models for each defense task, serving as the upper bound for CL without forgetting. (2) SeqLoRA[22]. A non-CL method conducts sequential task learning without any mechanism to mitigate forgetting. (3) Replay[23]. A traditional CL method replays the old tasks when learning new ones to reduce forgetting.
B. Overall performance
As shown in Table 1, our method outperforms all CL baselines across three task orders. Notably, our approach achieves an average defense success rate improvement of 2.92% compared to Replay (traditional CL method). The performance gains demonstrate that our method is effective in mitigating defense forgetting against the sequence of attack tasks. Our method also demonstrates high defense success rates across various training orders, highlighting its robustness. Furthermore, our method has a smaller gap (- 4.64%) in defense success rate compared to FT (a multi-task training method that does not forget), showing MoE in our method could reduce the overlap of new tasks and old tasks in CL.
