IV. CONCLUSION
In this paper, we introduce a novel MoE-based multi-agent continual defense framework that splits the network into non
overlapping groups, each serving as a different defense expert. This framework only activates the most suitable experts for the new task to address storage limitations while mitigating forgetting during continual defending against evolving attackers. We first construct an LLM-based multi-agent attack and defense framework to simulate CL attack-defense scenarios, which includes an attacker, a defender, and an evaluator. To reduce the storage space, we propose a MoE CL defense method that activates specific experts (derived from partitioning the model's neurons) to handle new attack tasks while freezing others. The experiment demonstrates the significant efficacy of our proposed framework. It consistently outperforms baseline methods in continual defense learning scenarios, achieving higher defense success rates across sequences of sequentially updated attack tasks.
